 The past year has been challenging for many, and it is our Doctors who have given the touch of care, by selflessly caring for us, and our loved ones.
 
This film takes viewers on the inspiring journey of Dr. Bhosale, who left no stone unturned to ensure many less fortunate children received life-saving medical attention before and during the pandemic. Gone too soon, Dr. Bhosale left behind his wife, kids and his dreams of building his own paediatric hospital. The film is a solemn reminder that like Dr. Bhosale, hundreds of doctors lost their lives during the pandemic leaving their dreams behind.
 
#TouchOfCare #PGSuraksha #DoctorsDay #NationalDoctorsDay

There are some actors whose work I really enjoy and none more so recently than Aditi Rao Hydari. Somehow she has a way of taking a part and making it her own, even without an arsenal of words. Mehrunisa in Padmaavat when she drops her head like a broken fawn. Priya Sharma in Geeli Pucchhi when she narrows those shoulders with the slightest of side glances as the perfect unattainable foil to a slouchy broody Konkona Sen Sharma. And who can forget Bibbo Jaan of Heeramandi; so vulnerable, so fierce and so intentional even as she sways and walks away from the viewers gaze. What it must take to shut everything out and still take everything in. To be supremely conscious and absolutely unselfconscious. To use beauty to turn the light on to what wounds us, what finds us, what breaks us, what remains with us. She says she does it by surrendering completely to her directors and their vision and I cannot begin to imagine how brave that is. How much I admire and respect this ability to give of yourself so completely for ultimately isn't that what creativity is? To be utterly vulnerable, totally trusting and relentless in your desire to suspend judgement and tell stories in your own original voice. Having gotten to know her better I see how this vulnerability is the light that comes shining through, unstudied, unfettered and utterly disarming.

Here she is in her leafy Bandra home, looking straight at us all with those fearless eyes with my carpet Sipahi, a reimagining of the Afghan war carpet tradition, from my collection "Majnun" created for Jaipur Rugs, at her feet. 
📸: Aditya Sinha
